  footnotes: []
english:
  title: An Evening Walk
  author: Lee Hyeon-son
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Hair loosened, a short staff in hand,
    Clothes worn just as they fall—
    I wander slowly through the empty courtyard
    where only my solitary shadow follows, broken and hesitant.

    A whisper rises in the twilight wind.
    The crescent moon tilts toward the western ridge.
    Withered flowers scatter from the old furrows,
    and autumn gourds hang cold on sparse vines.

    Dew beads on jade-green bamboo leaves.
    Tenuous smoke drifts from the ancient well.
    Birds flutter homeward in gathering flocks
    while deepening dusk settles in the forest.

    Even small creatures know to find their rest—
    why do I alone remain adrift?

    Returning, I lie in my chamber,
    and as I hum soft verses, stillness fills all four walls.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The image of the 'floating duckweed' (泛梗) suggests a person without roots, disconnected from the natural order where even the smallest creatures find their place.
  - key: ''
    value: The contrast between the natural world's harmony and the speaker's restlessness forms the emotional core of the poem—all creatures return to their dwelling as darkness falls, yet the poet remains unsettled.
